1. Introduction

Modern educational institutions manage complex course structures where each course consists of multiple modules, sub-modules, and learning units. However, many traditional course registration systems treat courses as flat entities, which limits flexibility and scalability.

This project presents a Java-based Course Registration System that models hierarchical course structures using the Composite Design Pattern. The system enables students to register for courses, explore module structures, and manage their academic records efficiently.

By applying core principles of object-oriented programming such as abstraction, inheritance, and polymorphism, the system ensures modularity, maintainability, and scalability.


2. Problem Statement

Educational systems often fail to represent the hierarchical nature of courses effectively. Courses typically consist of multiple layers such as modules and sub-modules, but traditional systems flatten this structure, making it difficult to:

Manage complex course content
Display hierarchical relationships
Extend or modify course structures

This project addresses the issue by implementing a structured system using the Composite Design Pattern, allowing both individual modules and grouped modules to be treated uniformly.


3. Objectives

The key objectives of this project are:

To design a scalable course registration system
To represent hierarchical course structures effectively
To implement the Composite Design Pattern in a real-world scenario
To enable student registration and withdrawal
To ensure proper data storage using file handling
To apply strong object-oriented design principles


4. Target Users

The system is designed for:

University Students – for course registration and viewing modules
Academic Administrators – for managing courses and module structures


5. System Features

The system includes the following core functionalities:

5.1 Course Registration

Students can register for available courses and withdraw if needed.

5.2 Hierarchical Course Display

Courses are displayed in a structured format showing:

Course → Modules → Sub-modules
5.3 Module Management
Add new modules
Remove existing modules
Organize modules hierarchically
5.4 Module Details

Students can view:

Module descriptions
Credit information
Prerequisites
5.5 Data Management
Student records stored using Java Collections
Persistent storage using file handling (.txt files)
5.6 Error Handling

The system handles:

Invalid inputs
Duplicate registrations
File handling errors



6. Technologies Used
Programming Language: Java
Concepts Used: Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
Data Structures: ArrayList, HashMap
File Handling: Java I/O
Design Pattern: Composite Design Pattern


7.1 Abstraction

An abstract base class or interface (CourseComponent) is used to define common behavior for both courses and modules.

7.2 Inheritance

Classes like Course, Module, and SubModule inherit from the base component.

7.3 Polymorphism

Methods such as:

displayDetails()
getCredits()

behave differently depending on the object type.

7.4 Exception Handling

Used to manage:

Invalid user inputs
Duplicate registrations
File-related errors



8. System Architecture

The system follows a modular architecture based on the Composite Design Pattern.

Key Components:
CourseComponent (Interface/Abstract Class)
Defines common operations
Course (Composite Class)
Contains multiple modules
Module / SubModule (Leaf Classes)
Represent individual learning units
Student Class
Handles student-related operations
RegistrationManager
Manages enrollment using collections
File Handler
Stores and retrieves registration data

This structure ensures:

Code reusability
Scalability
Clear separation of responsibilities

9. Working of the System
The system starts with a menu-driven interface
Students can:
Register for courses
View course hierarchy
Check module details
The system stores registration data in files
Modules are displayed in a tree-like structure using recursion
All operations are validated to avoid errors

10. Advantages
Flexible hierarchical course representation
Easy to extend with new modules
Clean and maintainable code
Real-world application of design patterns
Efficient data management using collections

11. Limitations
Console-based interface (no GUI)
Limited scalability for very large datasets
File-based storage instead of database

12. Future Enhancements
Add GUI using Java Swing or JavaFX
Integrate database (MySQL)
Add login/authentication system
Implement web-based version
Add recommendation system using AI/ML

13. Conclusion

The project successfully demonstrates the use of the Composite Design Pattern to model complex hierarchical systems. By integrating object-oriented principles with practical features like registration and file handling, the system provides a scalable and maintainable solution for course management.

It not only solves the limitations of traditional flat systems but also serves as a strong example of applying software design patterns in real-world applications.

